<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1863-03-14T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1863-03-14T00:00:00-05:00" n="19" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d19">
                        <head><persName type="from">Mr. Seward</persName> to <persName type="to">Mr.
                                Dayton</persName></head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 315.]</seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>,</placeName>
                                <date calendar="gregorian" when="1863-03-14"><hi rend="italic">March</hi> 14, 1863.</date></dateline></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir:</hi> Your despatch of February 26, No. 279, has
                            been received, and I have read with deep interest the paper which
                            accompanies it. The appeal of the Protestant clergy of France to their
                            religious brethren of Great Britain on the subject of the civil war of
                            the United States is so vigorous and just as to deserve the thanks of
                            the whole American people.</p>
                        <p>I am, sir, your obedient servant,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>WILLIAM H. SEWARD.</signed></closer>
                        <postscript>
                            <p><hi rend="smallcaps">William</hi> L. <hi rend="smallcaps">Dayton</hi>, Esq., <hi rend="italic">&amp;c., &amp;c.,
                                &amp;c.</hi></p>
                        </postscript>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>